pg 24
fig 20 is awesome
describes a spike in onchain fees followed by a increase in LN channels and a dying off of onchain fees (hopefully not a permanent die-off)
when on-chain fees are steadily low, the incentive to use LN is also lower
counterpoint: ln will always be more user-friendly (confirmations, ux)
pg 25
NEW CONCEPT: block-days saved
sept 2021: LN did ~663k tx, which is 332 blocks, which would take 2.3 days. therefore in sept2021, LN took 2.3 days of pressure off of the chain.
caveat: many of these LN-tx are micropayments, and would be too expensive for the chain, even at 0.01$ fees.
how much pressure relief is ideal? (in 2030 the block days saved will be well more than the days in a month, but will there still be enough chain-traffic to subsidize mining. this is only an issue once block rewards are not appealing enough in themselves.
pg 26
hubs are a convenience, and not strictly necessary, ergo privacy, centralization are non-issues
New concept: cut channels, cut nodes, hovering at 10 and 8% respectively
channels/nodes whos removal would disconnect entirely two parts of the network.
pg 27
measuring node clustering//clique-y-ness
peers are becoming more rational when opening new channels.
low barriers to entry to become a hub (capital, time) also point to centralization being a non issue
